const v16ReadA={id:"v16-read-a",kind:"passage",label:"Passage for Items 69-72",title:"Neighborhood Cooling Survey",description:"A city mapped afternoon temperatures at bus stops, playgrounds, and health centers. The hottest points were not always the places with the fewest trees; some had dark roofs, wide pavement, and little airflow. Planners first proposed planting only, but field teams also measured shade duration and surface materials. The revised program combined trees, light-colored roofs, drinking water, and shaded seating. Sensors later showed lower surface temperatures at treated sites, though planners warned that short monitoring could not establish how the measures would perform through every season.",alt:"Passage about heat mapping that found multiple heat causes, led to combined cooling measures, and produced lower short-term surface temperatures without proving year-round performance."};
const v16ReadB={id:"v16-read-b",kind:"passage",label:"Babasahin para sa Aytem 73-76",title:"Lalagyang Muling Ginagamit",description:"Sinubukan ng pamilihang bayan ang programang maaaring humiram ng matibay na lalagyan ang mamimili kapalit ng maliit na deposito. Marami ang gumamit sa unang linggo, ngunit kakaunti ang nagsauli dahil hindi malinaw kung saan ibabalik ang lalagyan. Naglagay ang pamunuan ng mga palatandaan sa bawat labasan, nagbukas ng tatlong return station, at ipinakita sa resibo ang halaga at paraan ng pagbabalik. Tumaas ang porsiyento ng pagsasauli. Gayunman, hiwalay na sinuri ang kalinisan ng hinugasang lalagyan; hindi sapat ang mataas na return rate upang patunayang ligtas itong gamitin muli.",alt:"Teksto tungkol sa programang deposito para sa reusable containers, problemang dulot ng hindi malinaw na balikang lugar, pagdagdag ng return stations at impormasyon, at hiwalay na pagsusuri sa kalinisan."};
const v16ReadC={id:"v16-read-c",kind:"passage",label:"Passage for Items 77-80",title:"Records Retention Review",description:"A regional office stored nearly every scanned document indefinitely. Search became slower, storage costs rose, and staff could not easily distinguish official records from temporary working copies. A review team classified records by legal, administrative, and historical value, then assigned retention periods and documented disposal approval. It also required holds for records connected to audits or pending cases. Storage use declined after duplicate working files were removed, but official records remained traceable through an index and disposal log.",alt:"Passage about classifying digital records, assigning retention periods, preserving audit or case holds, removing duplicate working files, and maintaining traceability through indexes and disposal logs."};
